          "content": "<p class=\"autor\">Enviada por Filhos de Dona Berê (Corumbá, MS) em 15 de Junho de 2012</p><p id=\"texto\">We are three sons of Mrs. Berê, and are going to play the feast in Aperê to give continuity to her feast. Presently she’s not here, she’s ill, but as long as she gets healed, she’ll participate in the festivities with us. She will be present..., so this feast for how long has been happening, it must be seventy years, that it is more than thirty, so, one<br>\nhundred years of the feast. Before I was born, the festivities already happened. <br>\n<br>\nToo good, as beautiful in my grandmother’s house as in my mother’s one. My mother got in charge after my grandma died. Mother went on with the feast because my brother was diseased and was undeceived by the physician. Then, my mother began to comply with a promise to the Saint. My brother got cured and she made up her mind not to stop, she would continue till the rest of her life with St. John feast but she wants that one of her sons keep her tradition, because it came from my grandma. As my ailing brother got cured, she doesn’t want to stop. She said that when she gets ill, she will be yet wishing a son to continue the feast. She told that to me, that she would be very happy if a son got he compromise to continue the feast. And so is the feast, we are talking thoroughly about it. <br>\n<br>\nThen, it became our responsibility, the mast, greasy pole. For every participant in the party contributes. “You are in charge of this, you are the Great King. And so on. The Great King is the one that gives the largest contribution, half a heifer or one heifer, on the like. (And before had my mother, before), But there’s no drink, no tippling. Only food and refreshments. He wants booze, it’s on his own account, and there are no liquors. Nothing, nothing, nothing. Plenty of food, dance till down, no brawl or arguments, nothing. And yet, they sleep here, on the benches. When next day rises I tell my mother: “get them away”. My brother- in-law switched off the sound and then he turned on and the feast continued. There is a boy here; he went down the slope with us. He descended lolling over. He paid his promise. Rolling over to the end of the slope. “Heaven’s guy”. We laughed so loudly, you don’t imagine. Because it’s all glee and joy, you go down; skipping and making a funny mess up. And he went down under the saint. Then he said: “I’m going”. Buddy, he went his way… Oh…his body…He said it was a promise he had made. He went down rolling over. Till the lower part down there. Ohm. Speaking truly, people took snapshots, but when ascending, for god’s sake, the legs get bad (you are not able to go up there). How many times I had an argument with my mom. Mom, you don’t go down, but she was stubborn and descended. And mother went many times to the…what cheers up the feast are the orchestras, the “charanga”. Then, when music is played everybody dances like in the carnival, goes and return, but the ascension…we would like that my mother could be here withy us. <br>\n<br>\nIf she were here, she would tell us about things, things that we unknown. But, henceforth we will begin. Here we’ll go on. If she bids us, we are answering to her. The feast is hers and will go on to the end. It is not because she is hospitalizes, sick, that no party will happen; there will be pray to St. John, we gonna tide Him; there is the mast, the<br>\ngreasy pole. All those things. Put it there, the mast is going to be put down, there will be prayers, because she is going to get a help. Let’s take him to church. Let’s do the same thing as before. What she did. OK? It’s all right, she will feel happy, sit over there, and she will be content with us, doing the right thing for her.</p>"
