          "title": "A dream of a man pulling a little lamb",
          "autor": "Enviada por Maria Paula da Silva (Corumbá, MS) em 15 de Junho de 2012",
          "excerpt": "Enviada por Maria Paula da Silva (Corumbá, MS) em 15 de Junho de 2012My name is Maria Paula da Silva...",
          "content": "<p class=\"autor\">Enviada por Maria Paula da Silva (Corumbá, MS) em 15 de Junho de 2012</p><p id=\"texto\">My name is Maria Paula da Silva. My grandma was St. John feaster. Since more than seventy years ago, when I realized I was somebody, aged five years, this feast was already carried out. I began the following way: She had a dream of a man pulling a little lamb, he went to different sides with the lamb and she told my mother this dream. <br>\n<br>\nThat time there was no gas stove, then my grandma was to the bushes to some wood and on a termite hill she found a saint image and caught it. My mother said it was St. John who was pulling the little lamb and she had to prepare a feast for him. She began to do the feast and at the age of 48 she passed away.<br>\n<br>\nThen, remained my mother who dies at 70 years of age, and I went on doing the feast and this continues up to present days. When I arrived in Corumba, according to my recollection, there were only 2 Saint John’s feast. It’s said that there was Mrs. Berenice too, but, where they mention, I don’t remember. I know that in the town of Jardim, there was a lady who lived near the Army quarters. My grandma arrived by this time, too. There were few St. John’s parties here in Corumba. <br>\n<br>\nThree by my recollections, but later on more parties began to happen. The Cururu, Siriri, Agripino, many times he hoisted the mast here with Cururu, and in front of my house he came to play for me. Now many of them are late and there’s no more. Siriri only happens in Caceres, only there you can hear a good Siriri. It was beat on wood, packing-box with the beater singing. It was cheerful. Are you gonna do? Oh, yes, (if God will). To do because not always we do much cake for the mass. To make a sandwich, hot-dogs, Paraguayan soup, something different. I do it in my own house, in the front door. There’s a prayer, lifting up of the mast, we go out in procession taking<br>\nthe mast, singing, playing music. <br>\n<br>\nAnd, at midnight we take St. John to the bath. Then, we return, serve a barbecue to the participants, the feasters, everybody. The feast is over. Next day there’s a small lunch, the left over surplus; many people come, come and cook a small lunch. Each ones helps with something, and what lacks, I complete. I’m the feaster; I must afford what is lacking. I have seven children. They help me to serve; now more than before because I’m already 76 years old, and they are who, may be, will continue the feast in the future.</p>"
